Anonymous Sun 02 Jul 2023 00:32:21 No.57691093 Report
Quoted By:
>continuing the discussion from last thread
>>57690798
For both of those things you said, I think that's the benefit of the anonymity that 4chan provides.
When you receive feedback on 4chan, you have no idea who it who the hell it comes from. It could be a random autist or is could be from an English professor. It's up to the writer whether to use that feedback and how to incorporate it, if they decide to. Whether its incorporated should be based on the merit of the feedback, not by who is posting the feedback. I'd argue we should never use tripcodes when giving feedback for that reason.

If you're a popular author giving feedback to a guy who's barely written, you don't want to have that big of a pull on their decision making because then they are writing the story you think they should be writing and not what they want to be writing. At the same time if you're an inexperienced author giving advice to an experienced one, hiding behind that anonymity makes it easier to offer your genuine thoughts without fear of it being attached to you if you end up looking like an idiot, or the author doesn't like it.

Not a writefag but I'm a drawfag and I noticed something relevant to the current discussion. Beginners who most desperately need advice will usually be the ones most ignored. I see people who have clearly only been drawing for a couple years at most asking for advice, but all I can come up with is "you just need more mileage." It's the same with stories. I'll open one up, read a few lines, think to myself "eh this prose kinda sucks" and move on.

Point being, just keep at it. Create for yourself, or if you really need those (you)s, start making stuff for a thread that isn't as saturated with artists/writers as this place is.

>She had shaggy grey fur and black horns. Her fiery amber eyes stood out.

A pure /hmofa/ story in theory would be that the man and woman would have symmetry in the amount of power and responsibility they have in the relationship. But this is never the case in real life because it's not efficient.
In reality, partners usually split up responsibilities according to their personal skills. One might take on finances, while another takes on housekeeping, etc. I guess what's acceptable for this thread is a relationship where it seems like both parties are together by choice, both maintain a substantial amount of input in order to keep things running smoothly, and neither dominate each other completely. Many here prefer traditional gender roles in their dynamic, which does entail the man having more control over the relationship, so I would say that /hmofa/ as a whole leans slightly more towards that end of the spectrum.
By contrast, a lot of /adhg/ *relationship* stuff has the anthro handling external work and finances and the human handling house and cooking duties. Those elements put the human in the role traditionally assigned to women, at least for westerners. This isn't enough to label the story /adhg/ on its own, but many stories add other elements like heavy social pressure or legal requirements that force the human to stay in line, in addition to having the anthro be physically stronger. There is a large female-centered power imbalance there that doesn't exist in a lot of the stories here, one that resembles abuse in some cases.
Negligent Discharge is a weird example because it has multiple paths. The Talia and Rebecca Paths belong here, but the Patricia Path doesn't.
TL;DR /hmofa/ is for pieces with comparatively equitable relationship dynamics, /adhg/ is for female-centered dynamics. Stories that blur the line should be posted in both, but there are some stories that only belong in one thread.
